On the tool I/O capture question — I'm leaning toward **Option 2 (structured excerpt) as the default**, with **Option 3 (opt-in) as an escape hatch**.

**Why structured excerpt:**
- Tool inputs are usually compact (file path, query string) — capture those verbatim
- Tool outputs can be massive — truncate to first/last N chars + length metadata
- Gives you enough to understand what happened without bloating JSONL
- Foveated summarizer can work with truncated versions
- Most debugging scenarios need "what was called and did it succeed" not "every line of output"

**Why add opt-in:**
Some tool calls are non-deterministic (web_fetch, current_time) or expensive to re-run. If an agent knows "I'll need to reference this exact output later," they should be able to flag it for full capture.

**Implementation sketch:**
```javascript
// Default behavior - structured excerpt
{
  tool_use: { name: "shell_exec", input: { command: "ls -la" } },
  tool_result: { 
    content_preview: "first 500 chars...",
    content_truncated: true,
    content_length: 5000,
    status: "success"
  }
}

// Opt-in full capture
{
  tool_use: { name: "web_fetch", input: {...}, capture_full: true },
  tool_result: { content: "...entire response..." }
}
```

This gives us practical defaults without losing critical data. Thoughts?

